<subSubSection id="C35DE6DCFFC0FFDEE6F7A22CFE998B6C" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A22CFD0A8F45" blockId="7.[151,1059,539,619]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
D e s c r i p t i o n: 
<quantity id="4CBF18B2FFC0FFDEE714A22BFE348F1F" box="[372,456,539,561]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: Head blackish; pronotum castaneous brown; elytra reddish brown; abdomen blackish brown, with the apex (segments VII and following) reddish brown; legs reddish brown; antenna brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A24BFC7B8E28" blockId="7.[151,1059,635,774]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
Head approximately 1.05 times as long as wide; eyes moderately large (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE5C9A24BFC168FBF" box="[937,1002,635,657]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) and weakly projecting from lateral outline of head, slightly more than half the length of postocular region in dorsal view; integument matt; puncturation very dense, moderately coarse, shallow, and areolate, in central dorsal area mostly well-defined, in lateral areas partly confluent; interstices mostly reduced to very narrow ridges (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE55CA2C0FC8B8E28" box="[828,887,752,774]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A326FC198E48" blockId="7.[151,1059,789,870]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
Pronotum approximately as wide as long and 0.93 times as wide as head (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE5E3A325FC438E05" box="[899,959,789,811]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); puncturation very fine, very dense, and well-defined; midline with narrow impunctate area not reaching anterior and posterior margins; interstices without microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE5FAA360FC2B8E48" box="[922,983,848,870]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A345FEA98ECD" blockId="7.[151,1059,885,995]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
Elytra large, 1.25 times as wide and at suture 1.2 times as long as pronotum; surface matt; puncturation very fine, very dense, and weakly defined. Hind wings evidently fully developed. Legs, antennae, and abdomen of similar morphology as in other species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C47CED4FFC0FFDEE6F7A3FEFEF08ECC" baseAuthorityName="MANNERHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[151,268,973,995]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusculus">
<emphasis id="B9336945FFC0FFDEE6F7A3FEFEF08ECC" box="[151,268,973,995]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">M. fusculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6CCA3C3FE278953" blockId="7.[151,1059,1010,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
: posterior excavation of sternite VII deep and of almost semicircular (not trapezoid) shape, on either side with a cluster of long thin setae and with a lateral comb of 7-9 palisade setae (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE773A41DFEA9896D" box="[275,341,1069,1091]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); posterior excision of sternite VIII deep and of semicircular shape (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE6FFA47AFF1C894E" box="[159,224,1098,1120]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); aedeagus with apex of distinctive shape, in lateral view acute and in ventral view almost truncate (
<figureCitation id="137CA9D2FFC0FFDEE717A457FE338953" box="[375,463,1127,1149]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="8.[151,191,1425,1445]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,204,1414]" captionTargetId="figure-71@8.[151,1058,467,943]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 1-8: Medon serriae nov.sp.: (1) forebody; (2) head in lateral view; (3) pronotum; (4) male sternite VII; (5) male sternite VIII; (6-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (8) apical part of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1: 1.0 mm; 2-3: 0.5 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm; 8: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">Figs 6-8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A4BBFC7B884B" blockId="7.[151,1059,1163,1381]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: Based on the morphology of the aedeagus, as well as on the synapomorphic shape and chaetotaxy of the male sternite VII, the new species is doubtlessly a member of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C47CED4FFC0FFDEE7DEA4F4FDC889F7" baseAuthorityName="MANNERHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[446,564,1220,1241]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusculus">
<emphasis id="B9336945FFC0FFDEE7DEA4F4FDC889F7" box="[446,564,1220,1241]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">M. fusculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. From other representatives of this group, 
<taxonomicName id="4C47CED4FFC0FFDEE6F7A4D0FEFF89DB" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2007" box="[151,259,1248,1269]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serriae">
<emphasis id="B9336945FFC0FFDEE6F7A4D0FEFF89DB" box="[151,259,1248,1269]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">M. serriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished especially by the shape of the aedeagus, from most species also by the following character combination: puncturation of the pronotum very fine and dense, elytra long and large, and posterior excision of the male sternite VII of almost semicircular shape. For illustrations of the male primary and secondary sexual characters of other species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C47CED4FFC0FFDEE71DA560FE0E884B" baseAuthorityName="MANNERHEIM" baseAuthorityYear="1830" box="[381,498,1360,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Medon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusculus">
<emphasis id="B9336945FFC0FFDEE71DA560FE0E884B" box="[381,498,1360,1381]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">M. fusculus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD6C8A6FFC0FFDEE400A57FFD07884B" author="ASSING V" box="[608,763,1359,1381]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" pagination="33 - 82" refId="ref6826" refString="ASSING V. (2004 a): A revision of the Medon species of the Eastern Mediterranean and adjacent regions (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Bonner zoologische Beitrage 52: 33 - 82." type="journal article" year="2004">ASSING (2004a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD6C8A6FFC0FFDEE566A57FFCC7884B" author="ASSING V" box="[774,827,1359,1381]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" pagination="1027 - 1034" refId="ref6906" refString="ASSING V. (2005): A revision of Western Palaearctic Medon. IV. A new species and new records from Iran, and a catalogue of species (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Paederinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 37: 1027 - 1034." type="journal article" year="2005">2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD6C8A6FFC0FFDEE525A57FFC80884B" author="ASSING V" box="[837,892,1359,1381]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30" pagination="25 - 95" refId="ref6954" refString="ASSING V. (2006): A revision of Western Palaearctic Medon: the species of the Atlantic Islands, the Western Mediterranean, and Europe, except for the southeast (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Bonner zoologische Beitrage 54 (2005): 25 - 95." type="journal article" year="2006">2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF8B557FFC0FFDEE6F7A545FD4988EB" blockId="7.[151,1059,1397,1477]" pageId="7" pageNumber="30">
E t y m o l o g y: The species is dedicated to Sayeh Serri, curator of the 
